<div id="review_3398923606" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3398923606" />
    <a title="Greta" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/111566858-greta"><img alt="Greta" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1586844759p2/111566858.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3398923606?book_show_action=true">Jun 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greta" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greta" href="/user/show/111566858-greta">Greta</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780451208637" href="/book/show/6655.The_Divine_Comedy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/111566858-greta?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3398923606" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2385723709002886805">Is there comedy in this comedy ?<br/><br/>I recently heard that there is no work of literature that people start to read but don’t finish more often than the „Divine Comedy“<br/><br/>This poem is Dantes imaginary journey of afterlife. He travels through hell, purgatory and paradise or heaven. Allegorically the poem represents the souls journey to god, beginning with the recognition and rejection of sin, followed by the penitent Christian life, which is then followed by the soul&apos;s ascent to God. Because Dante was al</span>
  <span id="freeText2385723709002886805" style="display:none">Is there comedy in this comedy ?<br /><br />I recently heard that there is no work of literature that people start to read but don’t finish more often than the „Divine Comedy“<br /><br />This poem is Dantes imaginary journey of afterlife. He travels through hell, purgatory and paradise or heaven. Allegorically the poem represents the souls journey to god, beginning with the recognition and rejection of sin, followed by the penitent Christian life, which is then followed by the soul's ascent to God. Because Dante was also very political, it can be interpreted in a light of a political conflict as well.<br /><br />But is there comedy? <br />Traditionally, plays and narratives have been divided into Comedy &amp; Tragedy. Easy put: a comedy is when the story turns out well for the protagonist and a tragedy is when the story turns out poorly for the protagonist and usually results in their death which is often due to their own actions. Still I do find it humorous that Dante used his depiction of hell to place individuals whom he didn't like in the different levels, or that his dead childhood crush guides him to the lightening. The harmony, unity, light and symmetry that is presented at the end of Dante's work is where the comedy is present and tragedy is absent. It accomplished what it set out to do in terms of giving meaning to the religious pilgrim wondering how to account for the "lost" nature of mankind.  In this light, it is comedic because of its unifying and harmonious vision presented and in light of the notable absence of tragedy in its resolution. Also it wasn’t written in Latin but in Italien, more legere and less sophisticated, which made it accessible to the lower social classes as well and changed Italien literature as a whole. <br /><br />This really is amazing poetry. It took me quiet some time to work through but Dante himself needed 12 years to write it and put a lot of thought into it. There are a lot of allegories to understand and I read a lot of interpretations along the way to comprehend what I was reading. It was absolutely worth it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2385723709002886805" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

